name: 3,5-difluoro-4-methoxybenzonitrile
Reason: To predict the melting point of 3,5-difluoro-4-methoxybenzonitrile, we analyze the effects of the functional groups present in the molecule on the basic benzene structure. The basic benzene molecule has a melting point of 5.5 degrees Celsius. Each substituent will affect the melting point as follows: Fluorine atoms introduce strong electronegativity, which can strengthen intermolecular attractions due to polarity; however, they are small and don't contribute significantly to the van der Waals forces, so we'll estimate an increase of +20 degrees each. The methoxy group (-OCH3) is both an electron-donating group and has a moderate size that may increase van der Waals forces, giving an estimated increase of +30 degrees. The nitrile group (-C#N) is a strong electron-withdrawing group and may increase dipolar interactions; however, its linear shape contributes less to van der Waals interactions compared to alkyl chains, so we'll estimate an increase of +25 degrees. Adding these together, we get an estimated total increase of 95 (20+20+30+25) degrees from the base benzene melting point.
